When I first saw the Papadia commercial I was both intrigued and perplexed. It looks tasty but what exactly is this pizza-themed sandwich? It’s certainly not a pizza-quesadilla or else they would have spelled it papa-”dilla”. Maybe Papa John’s is still trying hard not to be offensive since their split with their jackass founder? They claim it’s inspired by the “piadina” which is an Italian sandwich - so why not name it the papa-”dina”? Whether it be foolhardy oversight or calculated decision, I still had to try this enigmatic culinary creation.  I decided eventually to try the buffalo chicken experience. Upon opening the box, I was not deterred by the look of this mystifying hand-held concoction.  It honestly looked more like a lazy man’s cal-zone. It certainly didn’t live up to the commercial hype -- but  really what food on TV does? The cheese was melted, the buffalo sauce was oozing, and it was warm, so I was satisfied with my purchase based on early returns.  I bit into what I expected to be an exquisite elevation of chain-pizza grub, and much to my dismay, any satisfaction I found fleeting at best. Was it good? Sure. Was it great? Not even close. It was perfectly and absolutely mediocre. I’d describe it as the Ford Focus of food -- it does the job but it’s really not something I’m proud to have around my friends. It tasted good but was it really “better than a sandwich?” I’d say it depends on the sandwich it’s going up against.  Would I try it again? I mean sure, if I accidentally stumble into a PJ’s during a late night gallivant and it’s the fastest and most affordable thing to quell my drunken stupor, I’d eat it again. But with the plethora of options at our disposal for both pick-up and delivery in 2020, I’m a hard pass otherwise. Overall, I’d rate my Papadia a C+. (5 stars for the staff)
